> One more thing...in addition to finding a suitable system for the 
> nursing home, I must also try and convince the administration that an 
> "open" system of computing is a wiser choice than to go from a System 
> 36 to an AS/400 (which is what some people want).  Can anyone supply 
> with information that would support such an argument?  Can you tell me 
> of some good articles which I can go dig up?
> 
> Thanks again,
> Jason Heideloff
> Allegheny College
> Meadville, PA  16335

Before you try to convince them of this, I urge you to examine your motives for
wanting them to make this move. The  move from the S/36 to the AS/400 will be
far easier for them than the move to nearly any variety of openness (which I
assume, in a multi-user enviroment, you are equating to something derived from
or resembling UNIX). The operating environment will be familiar and has been
well tailored to relatively unsophisticated end users in small organizations
for over a decade. It doesn't boast the technical sophistication or the
hardware price-performance of the latest screamer from Sun or whomever, but
those are seldom the issue with this class of user. 

In short, figure out the valid BUSINESS (not technical) reasons why open
systems are better for this client, considering ALL costs including support and
the time of all system users, administrators, etc. - not just hardware costs,
and ignoring technical issues  like support of C++ that they correctly don't
care a whit about. If you can put together such reasons, they will be
convincing. If you can't, then inspect your own motives carefully. Do you want
them to move to open systems because those are what you know and like, while
the AS/400 isn't? Understandable, but not client-centered. If that's what it
comes down to, the high road is to urge them to stay with the AS/400 and to
find another consultant to help them with it.

