I think Doug hit it on the head, open is what you want it to be.  Forget the
concept of full portability between platforms.  Clearly define the problem,
and purchase the system that best solves the problem.  I'm not an IBM fan,
and the move from a Series XX to an AS/400 speaks for itself on the upward
compatability of IBM's own product.  Digital's "stuff" is almost always
upward/sideways compatible, and the ALPHA box is hot stuff.
 
Open to me means: seamlessly integrated.  Or in another way, it works, solves
your problem and meets all objectives.  So, a PC based MMI, connected to an
NT based server, using a data acquisition driver over ethernet, with
historical data collected on a VAX, staged to a corporate repository on
IBM.... only as long as it works!!!!
 
And concerning open... let's avoid anything that is proprietary like NT, DOS,
Windows, DECnet, OpenVMS, OS/2.... see, everything is proprietary.  Just do
your best to use "standard" packages, fully supportable and that work
together.
 
jff

