There are a number of factors that go into s36-> decision making:

(1) Costs of hardware  (AS/400 vs PC/LAN)- including existing hardware.

(2) Software - migrate existing software? (if yes, then AS/400 is it); if you 
are not crazy about what you have, then look around.

(3) User data files - (2) logic applies here.  Data files can be converted to 
any 'other' software cheaper than converting your old software.

(4) User competence - are they using PC's (for office,,,) now?  If yes, then 
PC/LAN may be the way.

PC/LAN's have come a long way,  You will find a number of stable multi-user 
applications on Novell, NT, MS-Windows,,,etc.  "Open" does not mean UNIX.

(5) AS/400 (advanced series) will support 'open', so this may be the way to 
go.

These cover only a small part of the decision tree.  I think the most 
important factor is $$$.   Both AS/400 and "open" systems with do the job 
from technical and availability points of view.

You should consider drawing up an RFP and see what comes up.

