Gentlemen:  all this talk about open.  I am amazed that....
 
We all agree!  Open has nothing to do with proprietary, it has to do with
solving a business problem with whatever technology give you the most value.
 I.E.  If a heterogenous environment, or homogenous environment: it matters
not as long as we solve the business problem, do it in a cost effective
manner, and allow the information to flow across platforms in a seamless way.
 
 
BOY, get that word seamless.  I had the fortune of implementing a downsizing
exercise that included 4000 users across a very wide area.  Downsizing,
client/server requires a careful look.  If your definition of client/server
is partly PC based, remember the term "Mass Customization", because you have
to plan carefully in such a customizable environment, especially when you
want to have some type of support and upgrade mechanism.  And then again
there is the "compatability" of products that really aren't.  We could talk
about documents, mail.
 
Documents: document strategy, old documents, new documents, WYSIWYG
documents, users that are terminal based, and PCs that are remote.
 
Mail: Proprietary Mail, x400, x500, internet, etc... sounds simple to me :-(
 
Technology wise, I was surprised no one mentioned network products that
included DEC: Pathworks, TeamLinks, and whatever groupware they are pedling.
 
Bottom line.  I'm impressed with the comments, and replies I've read.  The
responses seem on track, and hit of some experience, i.e., having been there.
 OPEN is whatever it takes, given you have the money to support it, and it
meets your business objectives.  Worry not about proprietary, because almost
everything is.  Think ahead, plan well, execute cautiously, develop
contingencies, and...good luck.  :-)
 
jff

